definition.value: A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid that is the 2-keto derivative of propionic acid. It is a metabolite obtained during glycolysis.
A compound formally derived from ammonia by replacing two hydrogen atoms by hydrocarbyl groups.
A compound formally derived from ammonia by replacing three hydrogen atoms by hydrocarbyl groups.
A compound formally derived from ammonia by replacing one hydrogen atom by a hydrocarbyl group.

An acyclic branched or unbranched hydrocarbon having one carbon-carbon double bond and the general formula CnH2n. Acyclic branched or unbranched hydrocarbons having more than one double bond are alkadienes, alkatrienes, etc.
A straight chain alkane composed of 9 carbon atoms.
A straight-chain alkane carrying 18 carbon atoms.
A straight-chain alkane with 19 carbon atoms. It has been found as a component of essential oils isolated from Artemisia armeniaca.
An alkane that has 21 carbons and a straight-chain structure. It has been isolated from plants like Periploca laevigata and Carthamus tinctorius.
A straight chain alkane containing 23 carbon atoms.
A straight-chain alkane containing 24 carbon atoms.
An alkane consisting of an unbranched chain of 25 carbon atoms.
A straight-chain alkane comprising of 26 carbon atoms.
A straight-chain alkane with 27 carbon atoms.
A straight-chain alkane containing 28 carbon atoms.
A compound formally derived from ammonia by replacing one, two or three hydrogen atoms by hydrocarbyl groups.
Any cyclic ether in which the oxygen atom forms part of a 3-membered ring.
Any monoacylglycerol phosphate obtained by hydrolytic removal of one of the two acyl groups of any phosphatidic acid or derivatives therein.
An amide is a derivative of an oxoacid RkE(=O)l(OH)m (l =/= 0) in which an acidic hydroxy group has been replaced by an amino or substituted amino group.
A monovalent inorganic anion obtained by deprotonation of one of the phosphate OH groups in diphosphoric acid.
A trivalent inorganic anion obtained by removal of all three protons from diphosphoric acid.
An oxopentanoic acid carrying an oxo group at position 2.
A indol-3-yl carboxylic acid that is butanoic acid carrying a 1H-indol-3-yl substituent at position 1.
An ortho- and peri-fused polycyclic arene consisting of a naphthalene and benzene unit connected by a five-membered ring.

The calcium salt of acetic acid. It is used, commonly as a hydrate, to treat hyperphosphataemia (excess phosphate in the blood) in patients with kidney disease: the calcium ion combines with dietary phosphate to form (insoluble) calcium phosphate, which is excreted in the faeces.
A calcium salt with formula CCaO3.
